A haunting, handcrafted fairy doll sits amidst a scattered ring of ripe berries—plums, cherries, and dark grapes—whose juices seem to bleed into her twisted form. Her skin is pale and textured like pressed paper or dried bark, flecked and soaked in splashes of deep red, as if painted by something more sinister than juice. One finger is held to her lips in a silent shushing gesture, its tip darkened, while her wide red eyes, rimmed in subtle shadows, stare out with an eerie stillness. Her wings are ragged and translucent, painted in drips of purple and wine-red hues, like watercolor soaked too deep into paper.
